    body: "A temporary disability placard is a hanging tag that gives the driver permission to park in handicap-marked spots for a limited period, usually six months to a year. Every state issues one through its Department of Motor Vehicles or its equivalent agency. Seniors get temporary placards after knee surgery, hip replacements, broken legs, strokes, cancer treatment that drains energy, or any other medical event that makes walking a long distance painful or unsafe. The placard does not give the driver any other rights; it only allows parking in spaces marked with the blue wheelchair symbol or marked Reserved for Persons With Disabilities.\n\nThe rules differ from state to state but follow the same general pattern. You fill out a one-page application from your state DMV. A doctor, physician assistant, nurse practitioner, podiatrist, optometrist, or chiropractor, depending on the state, signs the medical certification section. You take the form to the DMV in person, or mail it, or upload it through the DMV website. Some states charge a small fee, usually between $5 and $25, while others issue the placard for free. The placard arrives in two to four weeks, although same-day pickup is possible at some DMVs if you bring all the paperwork with you.\n\nA temporary placard looks like a small rectangular tag that hangs from your rearview mirror by a hook. The card has an expiration date printed on it, usually six months from the issue date in most states, twelve months in some. The placard is tied to the driver, not the car, so you can use it in any vehicle you ride in. Family members can drive you to appointments using your placard as long as you are in the car. Using the placard when the disabled person is not present is illegal in every state and can result in fines starting at $250.\n\nThis guide walks you through getting the application from your state DMV, having your doctor sign the medical part, submitting the paperwork, picking up your placard, and renewing it when the time runs out. Set aside about a week from start to finish, with one office visit to your doctor and one to the DMV. Many states also offer a special license plate for permanent disability, but for short-term needs like recovery from surgery, the temporary placard is the right tool. The handicap parking spot is closer to the building entrance, almost always wider to allow door swing for a walker or wheelchair, and usually has level pavement, all of which matter during recovery.",
